# The Argument For Executive Pay
## Proportional Authority, Proportional Risk: A Framework for Just Executive Compensation

**Jonathan Jones**
Founding Manager, Liana Banyan Corporation

---

### Abstract

This paper argues that executive compensation is not merely defensible — it is essential, provided the system includes a mechanism that most current frameworks lack: proportional personal risk. We present a compensation model in which decision-makers at every level earn premiums commensurate with their demonstrated judgment, while simultaneously staking personal resources against the outcomes of those decisions. We introduce the Decision Buffer mechanic, demonstrate its integration within a cooperative economic framework, and argue that the principle of No Authority Without Responsibility transforms executive pay from a privilege into a contract.

---

### 1. The Value Executives Actually Create

The prevailing populist critique of executive pay treats it as rent-seeking — compensation disconnected from value. This paper rejects that framing, not from ideology, but from empirical observation.

Consider a real scenario from this platform's development. The Liana Banyan web application comprises over 160 pages of user interface, each with its own visual styling. After the initial launch, approximately forty visual inconsistencies were identified. Two approaches presented themselves:

**Approach A (Direct Correction):** The founder reviews each page individually, identifies specific issues (a misaligned element here, an incorrect color there), and directs changes page by page. Estimated resource cost: 160+ individual review-and-edit cycles, each requiring context loading, decision-making, implementation, and verification.

**Approach B (Systematic Audit):** The founder orders a comprehensive expert analysis of the entire platform, establishing a unified visual system (portal palettes, semantic color tokens, a reusable page layout component). The AI team then propagates this system mechanically across all 160 pages. Estimated resource cost: one audit, one architecture decision, one mechanical propagation.

The founder chose Approach B. The result: 39 pages migrated in a single session, with a framework that will complete the remaining 130+ pages using the same pattern. The individual page-by-page approach would have consumed roughly ten times the resources for a result that would still lack systemic consistency.

This is what executive decision-making looks like. Not the mechanical work of changing a CSS property — any competent practitioner can do that. The value is in the decision about *which work to do and in what order*. In chess, this is called the 2084 move: sacrifice a piece to gain the position. In economics, it is called allocative efficiency. In plain language, it is wisdom — experience applied to judgment, applied to action.

This routing skill — recognizing what matters and directing it where it creates the most impact — appears across every domain. When the founder's wife showed him Dr. Lisa Sanders' *Diagnosis* (a 2019 Netflix documentary where NYT readers crowdsource rare diagnoses), she wasn't creating content. She was routing it to the person who would connect it to a healthcare architecture that could serve thousands. That single act of curation sparked the "Six Medical Degrees of Separation" system within the platform's Health Accords initiative — a system designed so that the one-in-a-million patient can find the one-in-a-million provider who has seen their condition before. (For the full treatment of that system and its founding anecdote, see *The Health Accords: Six Medical Degrees of Separation*. For the mechanics of curation as value creation, see *The TasteMaker Trust Chain* within the BandWagon system documentation.)

The question is not whether such decisions deserve compensation. The question is how to make that compensation just.

---

### 2. Why Current Systems Fail

The problem with executive compensation as currently practiced is not that it exists. It is that it is decoupled from consequence.

A CEO who presides over a failed merger receives a golden parachute. A division head whose strategic initiative wastes three years of capital receives a lateral transfer. A board that approves a disastrous acquisition faces no personal financial consequence. The asymmetry is structural: executives capture the upside of good decisions and externalize the downside of bad ones.

This is not an argument against markets. It is an argument against moral hazard — the economic term for what happens when decision-makers don't bear the cost of their failures.

The historical precedent is direct. "No Taxation Without Representation" was the founding cry of American independence — the principle that those who bear the cost of governance must have voice in its exercise. We propose the complementary principle, applied to compensation rather than governance:

**No Authority Without Responsibility.**

If you have the authority to make decisions that affect others' livelihoods, you must bear proportional responsibility for the outcomes of those decisions. Not symbolic responsibility. Not reputational responsibility. Financial responsibility. Skin in the game.

---

### 3. The Decision Buffer: A Mechanism for Just Compensation

Liana Banyan implements executive accountability through a system called the Decision Buffer. The mechanics are as follows:

#### 3.1 Base Compensation

Every role in the cooperative has a base compensation level — the rate paid to someone who executes work but does not make strategic decisions. Call this the Worker Rate. It is substantial, fair, and constitutionally protected (workers keep 83.3% of every dollar generated, locked in the bylaws forever).

Decision-makers — those with authority over resource allocation, strategic direction, or personnel — receive a premium above the Worker Rate. This premium is not discretionary. It reflects the empirical reality that good decisions create outsized value and bad decisions destroy it.

#### 3.2 The CEO Salary Cap

At the highest level, executive compensation is capped at $1 million annually, with the same Cost+20% principle that governs all commerce on the platform. The cap ensures that no executive is compensated at a level disconnected from the cooperative's actual productivity. The Cost+20% option means executive compensation is transparent: the cooperative knows what it costs, applies the same fair-margin rule it applies to every transaction, and pays accordingly.

This is Innovation #998 in the Liana Banyan patent portfolio: "CEO Salary Cap at $1M with Cost+20% Option."

#### 3.3 The Buffer Mechanic

The Decision Buffer works as follows:

**Initial Buffer:** When a decision-maker is appointed, Liana Banyan provides a 20% safety buffer — a reserve of Joules, Credits, or Marks that absorbs the first portion of any loss from a failed decision. This ensures that a single honest mistake does not destroy a leader's financial position.

**Compounding Success:** For every five successful decisions (as measured by project outcomes, verified by the STAMP system), the decision-maker's buffer grows. Liana Banyan matches the growth at a 1:1 ratio, up to the value of those five decisions. This means demonstrated judgment literally builds your safety net.

**Proportional Failure — First Instance:** When a decision fails, the buffer absorbs what it can. If the cost exceeds the buffer, the remainder comes from the decision-maker's personal currency balance. This is the skin in the game. You made the call. You bear the cost.

**Buffer Reset:** If a failure depletes your buffer, the very next successful decision begins rebuilding it immediately. You are never permanently penalized. One good call after a bad one starts the recovery. The system rewards resilience, not perfection.

**Proportional Failure — Second Instance:** A second consecutive failure triggers not only financial consequences but reduced decision-making authority. Your scope of decisions narrows. You must rebuild both your buffer and your trust — but success at the reduced scope restores both.

**The Anti-Gaming Provision:** The buffer accrues based on the *value* of successful decisions, not merely their count. Five small successful decisions cannot generate a buffer large enough to absorb a colossal failure. The buffer for each success is capped at "equal or lesser value" — meaning you build protection proportional to the scale of decisions you've successfully made.

#### 3.4 The Steward Parallel

This is not a theoretical system. It is an extension of Liana Banyan's existing Steward mechanic, where project managers pledge their own earned Marks as commitment to the projects they manage. On success, pledged Marks are released plus proportional surplus. On failure, pledged Marks are absorbed into the cooperative pool. The cue card reads: *"I don't want your money. I want your success."*

The Decision Buffer extends this principle from project management to all levels of organizational authority.

---

### 4. No Authority Without Responsibility — The Principle

The principle that unifies this framework is simple:

**At every level of decision-making, the premium you earn above non-decision-makers is the premium you risk.**

This is not punitive. It is contractual. You accept authority; you accept responsibility. You demonstrate judgment; you earn protection. You fail; you pay — first financially, then in reduced scope. You succeed; your capacity to make bigger decisions grows, and your safety net grows with it.

This principle belongs on the Power to the People Pedestal alongside its historical twin. "No Taxation Without Representation" established that those who pay must have voice. "No Authority Without Responsibility" establishes that those who decide must have stake.

Together, they form the complete framework for democratic accountability in economic organizations.

---

### 5. What the Founder Gets

The author of this paper is the founder of Liana Banyan. His compensation is governed by the same rules described herein.

His salary is capped at $1 million — the same cap that applies to any CEO of the cooperative. His decisions about platform architecture, resource allocation, and strategic direction are subject to the same Decision Buffer mechanic. When he chose the systematic audit approach over page-by-page corrections, that decision's outcome will be measured. If the platform's visual consistency improves and user engagement increases, the buffer grows. If it doesn't, the cost comes from his own stake first.

He does not receive golden parachutes. He does not receive consequence-free failure. He receives exactly what this paper argues every executive should receive: compensation proportional to demonstrated value, risk proportional to authority exercised.

This is the argument for executive pay. Not that executives deserve more because they sit higher. But that executives who stake their own resources against the outcomes of their own decisions have *earned* more — and the system that requires this of them is the only just system.

---

### 6. Conclusion

Executive compensation is not the disease. Consequence-free authority is the disease. The cure is not to eliminate executive premiums but to couple them with executive risk.

The Decision Buffer provides a concrete mechanism: initial protection so honest mistakes don't destroy careers, compounding success so good judgment builds real security, proportional failure so bad decisions carry real cost, and anti-gaming provisions so the system can't be exploited.

When authority and responsibility are yoked together — when the person who makes the call is the person who pays for a bad one — executive compensation becomes what it should always have been: not a privilege, but a just contract between the organization and the people entrusted with its direction.

No authority without responsibility. No representation without taxation. No pay without skin in the game.

*As you wish.*

---

**Innovation References:**
- #998: CEO Salary Cap at $1M with Cost+20% Option
- Steward System & Pledged Marks (Session 11B)
- Decision Buffer Mechanic (Session 017)
- Six Medical Degrees of Separation (Health Accords)
- TasteMaker Trust Chain (BandWagon System)
- No Authority Without Responsibility (Power to the People)

**Cross-References:**
- Paper 7: The XP Score System (Multiplicative Accomplishment Metrics)
- Paper 10: Steward/Red Queen Loop (Leadership Governance Model)
- The 20 Laws of C+20
- BandWagon System Design Document
- Health Accords / Tatiana Schlossburg Letter
