## 9. Conclusion

The Canister System addresses the small-scale manufacturing gap through modularization rather than miniaturization. Where existing solutions shrink industrial equipment to desktop size, the Canister System rethinks containment, clamping, and pressure delivery from first principles.

The dual-mode pressure architecture — gravity for casting materials on M/L/XL pistons, screw press for thermoplastics on the S piston — creates a system that serves two distinct manufacturing markets with the same modular canister/sleeve/sprue infrastructure. The S piston with an 8" screw press handle achieves 5,207 PSI, matching or exceeding the Morgan Press Desktop Injection Molding Machine (5,000 PSI, ~$1,200+) — the highest-rated desktop molder on the market — at a fraction of the cost and with 90-98% cheaper molds.

The break-even analysis confirms the Canister System's position as the bridge tool between 3D printing and production: for typical small parts, injection molding via Canister beats FDM at ~15-20 units and SLA at ~8-10 units, with time savings of 85-97% and superior material properties.

The hex-keyed twist-lock assembly reduces setup from hours to minutes. The stackable sprue chain enables multi-part production in a single pressure cycle. The 3D-printed A/B canister approach reduces per-mold cost by 90-98% compared to machined alternatives. And the natural routing principle — small piston for high pressure, large piston for high volume — makes the system intuitive to use without requiring pressure calculations from the maker.

For cooperative manufacturing networks, the Canister System is both a PRODUCT (sellable kits and mold libraries) and INFRASTRUCTURE (enabling decentralized production nodes). It turns any member with a 3D printer and a Canister kit into a potential injection mold operator — for casting materials out of the box, and for thermoplastics with the screw press attachment.

**The bottom line:** The S piston with screw press doesn't just reach into thermoplastic territory — it MATCHES the Morgan Press, the market leader, on maximum pressure while costing 70-85% less, with molds that cost 90-98% less, and a modular stackable architecture that no competitor offers at any price.

