## Appendix A: Statistical Analysis of the 50% Production Buffer

### A.1 The Buffer Hypothesis

The Liana Banyan model budgets production costs at 150% of estimated costs:

$$C_{budgeted} = 1.50 \times C_{estimated}$$

This section analyzes whether this buffer provides adequate coverage against cost variance.

### A.2 Observed Cost Variance

From internal prototype-to-production data across desktop (SLA, FDM) and industrial (SLS, injection molding) processes:
- Mean cost variance: +2.8% above estimate
- Standard deviation: 3.1%
- Coefficient of variation (CV): 3%
- Distribution: Approximately normal, slight right skew

### A.3 Buffer Coverage Calculation

For a normal distribution with CV = 3%:

| Sigma Level | Cost Overrun | Buffer Covers? |
|-------------|--------------|----------------|
| 1σ | +3% | ✓ (50% buffer) |
| 2σ | +6% | ✓ (50% buffer) |
| 3σ | +9% | ✓ (50% buffer) |
| 4σ | +12% | ✓ (50% buffer) |
| 5σ | +15% | ✓ (50% buffer) |
| 6σ | +18% | ✓ (50% buffer) |

The 50% buffer provides coverage beyond 6σ—a probability of less than 0.00034% that costs exceed the buffer under normal variance conditions.

### A.4 Fat Tail Considerations

Real-world cost distributions exhibit "fat tails"—extreme events occur more frequently than normal distributions predict. Even assuming a Student's t-distribution with ν=3 (heavy tails), the 50% buffer provides >99.5% coverage.

### A.5 Conclusion

The 50% production buffer is statistically robust against cost variance under any reasonable distributional assumption. The primary risk is not variance but structural disruption (supply chain collapse, force majeure)—which is addressed through the distributed node architecture rather than financial buffers.

