# VERSION 2: MORE DETAILS (Swimming)
## For investors, partners, journalists, municipal leaders. 5-7 pages.

---

## The Grand Experiment

The hypothesis is simple: if you give people the tools, the training, and the ownership, they will build a manufacturing economy that outperforms the extractive model.

Not because they're altruistic. Because they're self-interested — and cooperative ownership aligns self-interest with collective benefit. When the person running the injection molder owns a share of the marketplace, the quality standards, and the patent portfolio that protects the designs, they don't cut corners. They can't — their own reputation, their own revenue share, their own future equipment placement all depend on doing good work.

This is not a theory. The infrastructure is built. The equipment is priced. The escalation ladder is defined. The first products are in production planning.

The experiment asks one question: **does it work?**

## The Thesis

The first Industrial Revolution centralized production. The digital revolution centralized platforms. The 2nd Second Industrial Revolution decentralizes BOTH — placing manufacturing equipment at community-owned nodes, funded cooperatively, operated by meritocratically selected members, and connected through a shared digital marketplace.

## The Four-Level Manufacturing Escalation

| Level | Equipment | What You Are | Entry Cost (1/3) | Marks Required |
|-------|-----------|-------------|------------------|----------------|
| 1 | Canister System (manual) | **Maker with a printer** | $250-400 (full) | 0 |
| 2 | Desktop Molder (Babyplast) | **Maker with a bench** | ~$6,700 | 2,000 |
| 3 | SLS Machine | **A SHOP** | ~$5,000-$17,000 | 2,000+ |
| 4 | Industrial Press | **A FACTORY** | ~$16,000-$66,000 | 5,000 |

### Level 1: The Kit
The Canister System matches the Morgan Press on injection pressure (5,207 vs. 5,000 PSI) at 70-85% lower cost with 90-98% cheaper molds. It processes PP, PE, and ABS for small parts. The kit trains the operator, produces real products, and earns Marks toward the next level.

### Level 2: The Bench
Desktop electric molders (Babyplast, APSX-PIM) provide 15-45 second cycle times. A Partner who's earned 2,000 Marks through proven manufacturing contribution qualifies for cooperative co-funding. The 1/3 model distributes risk.

### Level 3: The Shop
SLS is when a maker becomes a business. No molds required — any STL file becomes a production-grade nylon part. A shop with Canister + Babyplast + SLS serves any order: small batch, high volume, or custom complex.

### Level 4: The Factory
Industrial presses with steel molds for 50,000+ parts/year. Senior Partners with Guild backing. The cooperative network's manufacturing backbone.

## The Economics

At 100 Level 2-3 Nodes: 1,000,000+ parts/year. $1-10M in annual GMV. 83.3% to operators, 16.7% to platform. Each Node is a local business — local rent, local supplies, local customers. Not a franchise — a cooperatively funded, independently operated manufacturing business.

## The Cold Start

Kickstarter Campaign 1 (SlottedTop, 15,000 units) → funds bounty pool → bounties recruit makers → makers earn Marks → Partners qualify for equipment → Nodes produce next campaign's products → revenue funds more bounties → repeat.

The network is self-funding. Each cycle grows because every transaction funds the next node.

## Why This Is an Experiment

Because nobody has tried this at this scale, with this structure, with these tools.

Cooperative manufacturing exists. Maker spaces exist. Bounty platforms exist. Desktop injection molding exists. SLS exists.

Nobody has connected them all through a single Marks economy where playing a game on a website → earning manufacturing credentials → qualifying for equipment co-funding → operating a shop → earning revenue share on a portfolio protected by 10 provisional patents and 1,511 formal claims.

This is the experiment. The 2nd Second Industrial Revolution.

If it works, it's a template. Any community, any product category, any country. The playbook is open. The technology is accessible. The cooperative structure is replicable.

If it works, the grand experiment saves the world — not through charity, but through ownership.

