# VERSION 2: MORE DETAILS (Swimming)
## For investors, partners, journalists, and serious collaborators. 5-7 pages.

---

## The Problem: Manufacturing's Missing Middle

Between "I have an idea" and "I have a factory" lies a valley of death that kills most physical products. The numbers:

- A single injection mold costs $15,000-$80,000
- A desktop injection molder costs $800-$25,000 and requires $200-$2,000 machined aluminum molds per part
- Hiring a manufacturing team requires HR, payroll, benefits, office space, and months of recruitment
- Contract manufacturers require minimum order quantities of 1,000-10,000 units
- The break-even point for traditional injection molding vs. 3D printing is 500-5,000 units

For a cooperative platform building physical products — hex terrain tiles, modular injection molding kits, gaming accessories — this gap is lethal. You can't hire a team until you have revenue. You can't get revenue until you have products. You can't have products until you have a team.

## The Solution: Bounties All the Way Down

Liana Banyan's answer is to replace the entire traditional manufacturing recruitment pipeline with a bounty-based Marks economy.

**The X-Ray Bounty Arena** (Production System #28) gamifies quality assurance across the platform. Members activate "X-Ray Goggles," scan any page for errors, and earn Marks for finding, documenting, and fixing problems. A Mario-style coin animation provides dopamine feedback. A daily tracker shows progress. Role badges (Scout, Scribe, Fixer) emerge organically from contribution patterns.

But here's where it gets interesting: the same Marks economy that powers digital QA also powers **physical manufacturing**.

**The Canister System** (Innovation #2022) is a modular injection molding architecture. Standardized 3D-printed A/B mold canisters with hex twist-lock assembly, stackable sprue chains, and a dual-mode pressure system. The S piston with screw press achieves 5,207 PSI — matching the Morgan Press, the market leader, at 70-85% lower cost with 90-98% cheaper molds.

To build 5,000 of these systems requires: CAD designers, 3D print validators, materials sourcers, mold engineers, assembly process designers, QA protocol writers, packaging designers, and fulfillment operators. Traditionally, this means 8-15 hires, $500K+ in salaries, and 6-12 months of recruitment.

In the Liana Banyan model, every one of those roles is a **bounty**.

## The Escalation: Bounty → Contract → Partnership

Contributors move through three tiers based on aggregate Marks:

**Tier 1 — Bounty Hunter (0-500 Marks):** Pick up tasks. Print a test piece. Verify a tolerance. Write a QA procedure. Each task earns 10-300 Marks depending on complexity. No commitment, no contract. Just do the work.

**Tier 2 — Contractor (500-2,000 Marks):** At 500 Marks, you unlock recurring task assignments, a 1.5x Marks multiplier, priority on new bounties, and access to advanced CAD files. This is a lightweight relationship — not employment, but reliable engagement.

**Tier 3 — Partner (2,000+ Marks):** At 2,000 Marks, you unlock revenue share on products you helped develop (the cooperative's 83.3% creator split applies to your components). You become a Factory Node seed — first in line for manufacturing equipment placement. Your name goes on the product permanently. You can propose new products funded by the cooperative treasury.

**The critical insight:** No applications. No interviews. No negotiations. The Marks ledger is the resume. The threshold is the interview. The revenue share is the contract. A teenager printing test pieces can reach Partner faster than an engineer who fills out a form and stops.

## The Numbers

**Canister System at scale:**
- 5,000 kits at estimated $150-300 BOM = $750K-$1.5M production cost
- Cooperative retail at C+20%: $180-360 per kit
- Market-competitive retail: $249-499 (vs. Morgan Press at $1,200+, Galomb at $1,100)
- Revenue at 5K units: $1.25M-$2.5M
- Break-even on S piston vs. FDM 3D printing: ~15-50 units depending on part class

**SlottedTop (Kickstarter Campaign 1):**
- 15,000 units at estimated $2-5 BOM = $30K-$75K production cost
- Kickstarter retail: $15 per unit
- Revenue at 15K: $225K
- Funds initial bounty pool for Canister System development

**The flywheel:** Kickstarter Campaign 1 (SlottedTop) funds bounties → bounties recruit manufacturing team → team builds Canister Systems → Canister Systems enable Factory Nodes → Nodes produce products for Campaign 2-13 → each campaign funds more bounties → repeat.

## The Membership Conversion Engine

Non-members can play the X-Ray Bounty Game and earn Marks — but their Marks decay at a half-life rate. Every 30 days, unprotected Marks halve.

For $5/year, Marks become permanent — backed by the cooperative's patent portfolio (10 provisionals, ~1,511 formal claims). This is the cheapest possible membership tier, intentionally accessible.

The conversion pipeline: Play → Earn → Decay → Convert ($5) → Accumulate → Threshold → Contract → Partner.

At $5/year for 2,000+ engaged members, that's $10K+ in annual recurring revenue from people who are ALSO producing your products for bounty Marks. They're paying to work for you. Except it's not "for you" — it's for the cooperative they partially own.

## The Bounty Arena as a Product

The entire X-Ray Bounty Arena — coin tracker, three-tier error marketplace, design auction, self-generating bounties — is packaged as a licensable SaaS product for other websites.

- **Free** for any site that's an LB cooperative member
- **Paid SaaS** for non-member sites

This creates a triple flywheel: non-member sites pay for the tool → see the LB ecosystem → convert to membership → get it free. The bounty system that builds your products also sells itself as a product.

## Why This Matters

Most platform cooperatives struggle with the cold start problem: you need members to create value, but you need value to attract members. The Bounty-to-Partnership pipeline solves this by making the BUILDING of the platform itself the value proposition.

You don't join Liana Banyan because the platform is already great. You join because building it makes you a manufacturer, a contractor, a partner — with real revenue share, real products, and real equity in the cooperative's patent portfolio.

The industry backbone isn't a factory. It's a game that turns into a career.

