# VERSION 3: IN DEPTH (Deep Dive)
## Full academic/patent treatment. For attorneys, academics, institutional partners. 10+ pages.

---

## Abstract

We present a novel manufacturing recruitment and production architecture that replaces traditional hiring, contracting, and partnership processes with a gamified bounty economy. The system integrates three innovations: (1) the X-Ray Bounty Arena, a gamified quality assurance platform that awards Marks (a differential currency) for finding, documenting, and fixing errors; (2) the Canister System, a modular injection molding architecture achieving 5,207 PSI with 3D-printed molds at 90-98% lower tooling cost than existing desktop molders; and (3) a three-tier escalation pipeline (Bounty Hunter → Contractor → Partner) where aggregate Marks thresholds replace applications, interviews, and negotiations. We demonstrate that this architecture solves the cooperative cold start problem by making the construction of the manufacturing infrastructure itself the primary member value proposition, while simultaneously generating licensable SaaS revenue and converting non-members through a half-life Marks decay mechanism. Production targets of 5,000 Canister Systems and 15,000 SlottedTop hex terrain adapters are analyzed with preliminary BOM estimates and break-even calculations.

## 1. Introduction: The Cooperative Manufacturing Problem

Platform cooperatives face a structural disadvantage in physical goods manufacturing. Traditional platforms (Amazon, Etsy) act as intermediaries between existing manufacturers and consumers. Cooperative platforms, by contrast, often seek to own or coordinate the means of production — but lack the capital, expertise, and workforce to build manufacturing capacity from scratch.

The typical path requires: (a) raising capital through membership dues or external investment; (b) hiring a manufacturing team through traditional HR processes; (c) procuring equipment and materials through established supply chains; (d) building production capacity over 6-24 months before generating revenue. This sequence creates a capital-intensive, time-delayed value chain that most cooperative startups cannot sustain.

Liana Banyan Corporation (Wyoming C-Corp, filed 11/21/2025) addresses this structural problem through what we term the "Industry Backbone" — a vertically integrated manufacturing architecture built entirely through bounty-based Marks incentives, requiring no traditional hiring and minimal upfront capital.

## 2. Component Systems

### 2.1 The X-Ray Bounty Arena (Production System #28)

The X-Ray Bounty Arena gamifies platform quality assurance through six integrated innovations:

**#2023 — X-Ray Error Bounty Game:** Members activate an overlay mode ("X-Ray Goggles") that makes page elements inspectable. Clicking an error triggers a Mario-style coin flip animation (Web Audio API-generated NES chime, togglable) and awards Marks. A persistent daily tracker shows errors found, documented, and fixed, plus streak days.

**#2024 — Three-Tier Error Marketplace:** Errors flow through Find (click-to-report, smallest Marks) → Document (describe the error, medium Marks) → Fix (propose a solution, largest Marks). Members can specialize as Scouts, Scribes, or Fixers. Multiple people earn from the same error — a grandmother clicking a misaligned button and a developer proposing the CSS fix both earn.

**#2025 — Design Auction Arena:** Proposed design changes display for 10 seconds each in a timed slideshow. Members bid Marks (pledged as governance weight, not spent) on changes they want implemented. Highest-bid design becomes active until replaced. 24-hour auction cycles run continuously.

**#2026 — Marks Half-Life Decay:** Non-members' earned Marks decay at a half-life rate (~30-day period). $5/year membership locks Marks permanently, backed by the cooperative's patent portfolio. This creates a smooth conversion funnel: play → earn → decay → convert.

**#2027 — Self-Generating Bounty Loop:** Members create AND fulfill their own bounties. Community members can amplify bounties by adding Marks to the pool. This creates a self-sustaining error economy with no central authority needed to prioritize fixes.

**#2028 — Bounty Arena as a Service:** The entire system is packaged as licensable SaaS — free for LB member sites, paid for non-members. This generates revenue while creating a conversion funnel for new cooperative members.

### 2.2 The Canister System (Innovation #2022)

A modular injection molding architecture with four standardized canister sizes (S/M/L/XL), hexagonal twist-lock assembly, stackable sprue chains, and dual-mode pressure delivery.

The S piston with 8" ACME screw press handle achieves 5,207 PSI — validated against the Morgan Press desktop injection molder (5,000 PSI, retail ~$1,200+). Compatible thermoplastics: LDPE, HDPE, PP, and high-flow ABS. Break-even vs. FDM 3D printing: 15-50 units for typical small parts with in-house 3D-printed molds.

Key differentiators vs. all existing desktop injection molders:
- **Stackable** (2-3 high for thermoplastics, 6+ for gravity casting)
- **3D-printed molds** ($5-25 each vs. $200-2,000 machined aluminum)
- **Dual-mode** (gravity casting AND thermoplastic injection in same system)
- **Portable** (no bench mount, no power for gravity mode)
- **70-85% lower cost** than nearest competitor at comparable pressure

Patent candidate — Provisional #11. Critical novelty gap: no prior art discloses a screw-press injection piston as a removable, interchangeable module within a multi-configuration canister system.

### 2.3 The Bounty-to-Partnership Pipeline (Innovation #2029)

Three-tier escalation based on aggregate Marks:

| Threshold | Status | Multiplier | Unlocks |
|-----------|--------|-----------|---------|
| 0-499 | Bounty Hunter | 1.0x | Task-by-task bounties |
| 500-999 | Contractor | 1.5x | Recurring tasks, priority bounties, advanced CAD access |
| 1,000-1,999 | Senior Contractor | 1.75x | Bounty creation, design review, monthly meetings |
| 2,000-4,999 | Partner | 2.0x | Revenue share (83.3% split), Factory Node seed, IP Ledger, Steward eligibility |
| 5,000+ | Senior Partner | 2.5x | Product proposal rights, Guild Treasury access, mentorship role |

No applications. No interviews. No negotiations. Aggregate Marks are the sole determinant. This is a meritocratic escalation mechanism where contribution IS credential.

## 3. The Industry Backbone Architecture

### 3.1 Integration Model

The three systems compose into a single vertical:

```
X-Ray Bounty Arena (digital QA) ──→ Marks Economy ──→ Manufacturing Bounties
        │                                                      │
        ▼                                                      ▼
  Half-Life Decay ──→ $5/year Membership ──→ Patent Portfolio Backing
        │                                                      │
        ▼                                                      ▼
  Bounty Hunter ──→ Contractor ──→ Partner ──→ Factory Node Operator
        │                                                      │
        ▼                                                      ▼
  Kickstarter Revenue ──→ Bounty Pool ──→ Products ──→ More Revenue
```

### 3.2 The Cold Start Solution

The Industry Backbone solves the cooperative cold start problem by making infrastructure-building itself the primary value proposition:

1. **Kickstarter Campaign 1** (SlottedTop) raises $5K-$100K
2. 10% of revenue seeds the manufacturing bounty pool
3. Bounties recruit CAD designers, 3D printers, materials sourcers, QA engineers
4. Contributors earn Marks → reach Contractor → reach Partner
5. Partners build the Canister System production pipeline
6. Canister Systems enable Factory Nodes
7. Factory Nodes produce products for Campaigns 2-13
8. Each campaign funds more bounties
9. The network grows without traditional hiring

The genius is that each person building the system is simultaneously: (a) earning income (Marks → real value), (b) building their own future manufacturing capacity (Factory Node path), (c) contributing to a patent portfolio they partially own, and (d) playing a game they enjoy.

### 3.3 Production Targets

**Phase 1 — SlottedTop (Campaign 1):**
- 15,000 units, injection molded PP
- BOM: ~$2-5/unit, total $30K-$75K
- Kickstarter retail: $15/unit
- Gross: $225K - $30-75K COGS = $150-195K
- 10% to bounty pool: $15-20K → seeds ~200-400 bounty tasks

**Phase 2 — Canister System (Separate Project):**
- 5,000 kits, mixed manufacturing (machined + 3D printed + assembled)
- BOM: $150-300/kit, total $750K-$1.5M
- Retail: $249-499/kit
- Revenue: $1.25M-$2.5M
- Built entirely through bounty-recruited manufacturing team

## 4. The Licensable Product Layer

The Bounty Arena operates as both internal infrastructure AND external product:

- **Internal:** Drives QA, recruits manufacturers, converts members
- **External:** Licensable SaaS for any website wanting gamified QA
- **Pricing:** Free for LB member sites, paid subscription for non-members
- **Conversion:** Non-member sites experience the system → see LB benefits → join cooperative → get it free

This is what we term "infrastructure-as-product" — the tool that builds the platform is also the tool that sells the platform.

## 5. Economic Model

### 5.1 Revenue Streams

| Stream | Annual Estimate (Year 1) | Source |
|--------|-------------------------|--------|
| Kickstarter Campaigns (13) | $22K-$276K | Backers |
| Canister System Sales | $1.25M-$2.5M | Makers/hobbyists |
| Membership ($5/year) | $10K-$100K | Bounty game players |
| Bounty Arena SaaS | $5K-$50K | External sites |
| Factory Node Equipment | $50K-$200K | Node operators (1/3 model) |
| **Total Year 1** | **$1.34M-$3.13M** | |

### 5.2 Cost Structure

| Cost | Annual Estimate | Notes |
|------|----------------|-------|
| Canister System COGS (5K) | $750K-$1.5M | Bounty-recruited production |
| SlottedTop COGS (15K) | $30K-$75K | Injection molded |
| Platform hosting | $5K-$15K | Firebase + Supabase |
| Bounty pool (Marks) | $50K-$150K | Converts to real value at membership |
| Kickstarter fees | $5K-$30K | 10% of campaign revenue |
| **Total Year 1** | **$840K-$1.77M** | |

### 5.3 Key Assumption

All manufacturing is performed by bounty-recruited contributors, NOT traditional employees. This eliminates: salary overhead, benefits, payroll taxes, office space, HR costs, and recruitment fees. The bounty Marks have real value (backed by patent portfolio, usable in cooperative economy) but are not cash — they're cooperative currency. This means manufacturing labor cost is denominated in Marks, not dollars, until the contributor converts Marks to goods/services within the cooperative ecosystem.

## 6. Conclusion

The Industry Backbone of Liana Banyan demonstrates that a cooperative platform can build vertically integrated manufacturing capacity without traditional hiring, without venture capital, and without external manufacturing contracts. The key innovation is the bounty-based Marks economy that serves simultaneously as: (a) gamified QA for the digital platform, (b) recruitment mechanism for physical manufacturing, (c) meritocratic credentialing system replacing traditional HR, (d) membership conversion funnel, and (e) licensable SaaS product.

The system's elegance lies in its self-reinforcing nature: playing a game on the website → earning Marks → converting to membership → taking manufacturing bounties → building products → selling products → funding more bounties → more players → more Marks → more manufacturers → more products.

The teenage 3D printer operator who reaches Partner status through pure contribution — without ever filling out an application, attending an interview, or negotiating a contract — is not an edge case. It is the design intent. DO THE WORK = GET THE STATUS is not a marketing slogan. It is the system architecture.

