## 4. Analysis

### 4.1 CO design as anti-misrepresentation infrastructure

Misrepresentation in platform recruitment takes multiple forms: exaggeration of typical outcomes, suppression of costs and time investments, conflation of gross and net figures, and selective presentation of success stories. COs address each of these forms through structural design rather than policy alone:

**Exaggeration of typical outcomes.** Conservative defaults ensure that the "first thing a member sees" is a modest scenario. The member must actively move sliders upward to see higher numbers, creating a physical and cognitive experience of departing from the baseline. This is more effective than a textual disclaimer, because the member's own agency in constructing the optimistic scenario makes them aware that it is a departure from the default (Thaler & Sunstein, 2008).

**Suppression of costs and time.** COs include time-investment variables (hours per week, time per delivery, preparation time) and compute hourly-rate equivalents. A member who models high revenue but also enters realistic time commitments will see that their effective hourly rate may be modest. This prevents the common gig-economy tactic of presenting gross revenue without accounting for time costs (Rosenblat, 2018).

**Conflation of gross and net.** The derivation engine separates gross transaction volume, platform margin, and creator share into distinct, labeled outputs. A member cannot mistake gross volume for their take-home service value, because the 83.3% creator share is computed and displayed separately.

**Selective success stories.** Because every member can generate their own scenario using the same tool and the same underlying model, the platform cannot selectively present "star" outcomes while hiding typical results. The tool is the same for everyone; the differences come from the inputs each member chooses, and those inputs are bounded by the constraints described in Section 3.2.

### 4.2 Comparison with MLM income calculators

MLM income calculators---the interactive tools provided by some multi-level marketing companies to help recruits estimate their potential earnings---represent the most direct comparison class for COs. A structural comparison reveals systematic differences:

| Design Dimension | Typical MLM Calculator | Contingency Operator |
|---|---|---|
| Default scenario | Optimistic ("diamond level") | Conservative (early-stage, modest) |
| Output format | Single point estimate | Range (low, expected, high) |
| Compensation model | Multi-level overrides, recruitment bonuses | Flat Cost+20%, no multi-level overrides |
| Time investment | Rarely modeled | Explicitly included with hourly rate |
| Cost deductions | Omitted or minimized | Included (ingredient costs, fuel, etc.) |
| Comparison to min. wage | Never shown | Computed and displayed |
| Underlying model visibility | Opaque | Fully transparent, inspectable |
| Saved artifacts | None | Mini business plans in portfolio |
| Mentor use | Mentor incentivized to inflate | Mentor held accountable by model |
| Regulatory framing | "Earnings potential" | "Service participation demonstration" |

The contrast is not accidental. COs are designed as the structural inverse of MLM income calculators: where MLM tools are optimized to convert recruits by showing the best possible scenario, COs are optimized to inform members by showing realistic scenarios and making the economic model transparent.

### 4.3 Comparison with gig-economy earnings estimates

Gig-economy earnings estimates occupy a middle ground between MLM calculators and COs. Platforms like ride-sharing and delivery services do provide some variable-specific information (e.g., earnings per trip, surge multipliers), but this information is typically presented in ways that favor optimistic interpretation:

- **Peak-hour bias.** Estimates are often drawn from high-demand time slots and favorable geographic markets.
- **Gross presentation.** Vehicle costs, depreciation, fuel, insurance, and self-employment taxes are excluded.
- **Algorithmic opacity.** The platform's pricing algorithm, commission structure, and bonus criteria are not fully transparent to workers (Dubal, 2017).

COs avoid all three patterns. Variable defaults are calibrated to non-peak, early-stage conditions. Costs are included in the derivation. The economic model (Cost+20%, 83.3% creator share) is fully visible and fixed. The result is that CO outputs are systematically more conservative and more transparent than gig-economy estimates, by design.

### 4.4 Temperament-adaptive presentation

Paper 2 describes how the platform infers a four-factor temperament profile for each member. COs use this profile to adapt how scenario outputs are presented, without changing the underlying computation:

- **Organizer temperament:** Detailed tabular breakdown, all derivation formulas visible by default, emphasis on precision and completeness.
- **Improviser temperament:** Visual, card-based layout with key metrics highlighted, formulas available on demand but collapsed by default, emphasis on actionability.
- **Connector temperament:** Narrative framing ("If you prepare 10 meals per week and serve 15 households, your monthly service participation may look like..."), with relational context (how this role connects to neighborhood needs).
- **Synthesizer temperament:** Systems-level view showing how role variables interact with platform-wide metrics, emphasis on understanding the whole rather than individual numbers.

This adaptive presentation draws on research showing that information processing style influences both comprehension and decision quality (Epstein, Pacini, Denes-Raj, & Heier, 1996). By presenting the same underlying data in the format most natural to the member's temperament, COs increase the likelihood that the information is actually understood and used, rather than glossed over or misinterpreted.

### 4.5 Mentor-mediated use and the Lighthouse Ladder integration

COs are designed to be used in conversation between a mentor and a prospective member, not merely as standalone self-service tools. This design reflects two findings from the literature:

First, de Jong and van Joolingen (1998) found that simulation-based learning is most effective when supplemented by guidance and scaffolding. A mentor can ask probing questions ("What happens to your hourly rate if you account for 30 minutes of preparation time per meal?"), suggest alternative variable configurations, and contextualize outputs with their own experience. This guided exploration produces deeper learning than unsupervised slider manipulation.

Second, the mentor-mediated model creates bilateral accountability. The mentor cannot exaggerate because the model is transparent---the numbers are right there, and the member can see the formulas. The member cannot later claim they were promised outcomes that exceed what the CO showed, because the scenario is saved in their portfolio. This bilateral transparency addresses the problem identified by Eby, McManus, Simon, and Russell (2000) that negative mentoring experiences often arise from misaligned expectations.

Within the Lighthouse Ladder hierarchy (Paper 1), CO proficiency is a certification criterion. Mentors at each level must demonstrate the ability to guide mentees through CO scenarios, interpret outputs, and answer questions about the underlying economic model. This ensures that the financial literacy embedded in the CO tool is transferred through human interaction, not just tool exposure.

---

## 5. Discussion

### 5.1 COs as situated financial literacy

Traditional financial literacy education suffers from a transfer problem: knowledge acquired in classroom or online settings does not reliably transfer to real-world financial decisions (Fernandes et al., 2014). COs address this by eliminating the transfer gap entirely. The "classroom" is the decision context itself; the "lesson" is the economic scenario the member is actively constructing; the "test" is the quality of the plan they save to their portfolio. This situated approach to financial literacy aligns with broader educational theory on situated cognition (Brown, Collins, & Duguid, 1989), which holds that learning is most effective when it occurs in the context where the knowledge will be applied.

The financial literacy embedded in COs is not generic but role-specific. A Meal Maker learns about food-service economics (meal pricing, ingredient costs, preparation time, customer acquisition). A Grocery Runner learns about delivery logistics (radius, time per delivery, fuel costs). An Ambassador learns about recruitment dynamics (conversion rates, retention, onboarding time). This specificity increases relevance and retention compared to abstract financial instruction about budgeting, interest rates, or debt management---topics that, while important, are not directly connected to the member's immediate decision.

### 5.2 The anti-extraction constraint

The Cost+20% floor, implemented as a hard constraint in the derivation engine, is perhaps the most distinctive feature of COs from a platform-design perspective. In most platform earnings calculators, the platform's take rate is either hidden, variable, or presented as a feature ("low commission rates!"). In COs, the 20% margin is visible, fixed, and non-negotiable. This has several effects:

- **Trust through constraint.** By showing members that the platform cannot extract more than 20%, COs build trust through visible limitation. The platform is saying, in effect, "We have tied our own hands, and here is the knot." This is a form of credible commitment (Schelling, 1960), made tangible through interface design.
- **No race to the bottom.** Because the Cost+20% floor prevents members from competing on margin (no one can offer services below cost plus 20%), the platform avoids the race-to-the-bottom dynamics common in gig-economy markets, where platforms and workers both lose as margins compress (Prassl, 2018).
- **Cooperative identity reinforcement.** The fixed margin visually and experientially reinforces the cooperative's identity as a shared-infrastructure model rather than an extractive platform. Every time a member uses a CO, they see the margin and understand where it goes (to platform infrastructure, governance, and shared services). This is a form of economic transparency that most platforms do not provide.

### 5.3 Limitations and future directions

Several limitations of the current CO design should be noted.

**Static calibration.** Current default values and ranges are set by platform designers based on early modeling and estimates. As the platform accumulates actual participation data, defaults and ranges should be recalibrated to reflect empirical distributions. Future work should implement adaptive defaults that adjust based on aggregated, anonymized data from members in similar roles and markets.

**Individual variation.** COs model a "representative" member in a given role, but individual outcomes vary based on factors not captured in the variable set (personal network size, cooking skill, local competition, marketing effort). Future iterations could incorporate member-specific variables drawn from their profile and history, producing personalized rather than generic scenarios.

**Longitudinal tracking.** The current system allows members to save scenarios but does not automatically compare projected outcomes to actual results over time. A longitudinal feedback loop---in which the CO tracks actual participation data against projected scenarios and surfaces discrepancies---would enhance both financial literacy and model accuracy. This is consistent with research on feedback loops in learning systems (Hattie & Timperley, 2007).

**Multi-role modeling.** Some members participate in multiple roles simultaneously (e.g., Meal Maker and Ambassador). The current CO system models roles independently. Future work should support multi-role scenarios that account for time allocation across roles and aggregate outcomes.

**Accessibility.** The slider-based interface assumes visual interaction. Future work should explore voice-guided and text-based CO interfaces for members with visual impairments or low digital literacy, consistent with principles of universal design (Mace, Story, & Mueller, 1998).

### 5.4 Ethical considerations

COs raise ethical questions that deserve explicit treatment. The conservative default calibration, while protective, could discourage participation by understating realistic outcomes. If defaults are too conservative, prospective members may conclude that platform participation is not worthwhile, even when it would be. The design team must balance protection against optimism bias with the risk of introducing pessimism bias.

The temperament-adaptive presentation raises questions about manipulation. If the system presents the same data in different frames based on inferred personality characteristics, is it nudging or manipulating? We argue that adaptation is ethical when the underlying data is unchanged and the member can access any presentation mode on demand. The system adapts *form* (tabular vs. narrative) but does not alter *substance* (the numbers and their computation). This distinction aligns with Sunstein's (2014) argument that transparency-preserving nudges are ethically defensible.

Finally, the use of CO scenarios as accountability artifacts in mentor-mentee relationships raises privacy considerations. Members should have full control over which scenarios are saved, which are shared with mentors, and which are included in their public portfolio. The current design gives members this control, but future implementations must ensure that platform governance does not create pressure to share scenarios involuntarily.

---

## 6. Conclusion

Contingency Operators represent a design approach to a problem that most platforms solve badly or ignore entirely: how to communicate economic realities to prospective participants honestly, transparently, and in a way that builds financial literacy rather than exploiting its absence. By embedding interactive, role-specific economic sandboxes directly into the cooperative platform, COs provide just-in-time financial education at the point of decision, enforce conservative defaults that counter optimism bias, make the platform's economic model visible and inspectable, and generate portable artifacts that serve as both planning documents and accountability records.

The CO system is not merely a feature; it is infrastructure for honest economic communication. Its design is informed by financial literacy research demonstrating the superiority of just-in-time, context-specific education over generic instruction (Lusardi & Mitchell, 2014; Fernandes et al., 2014); by behavioral economics principles of default calibration, framing, and real-time feedback (Thaler & Sunstein, 2008); by FTC guidance requiring typicality, substantiation, and context in earnings representations (FTC, 2022); and by simulation-based learning research showing that guided, constrained interactive models produce deeper understanding than either expository instruction or unguided exploration (de Jong & van Joolingen, 1998; Wouters et al., 2013).

Within the five-paper architecture, COs function as the member-facing surface of the cooperative's commitment to transparency. The Lighthouse Ladder (Paper 1) provides the human mentoring context in which COs are used. The Invisible Temperament system (Paper 2) adapts CO presentation to individual cognitive style. The Self-Funding Economic model (Paper 3) provides the structural invariants (Cost+20%, three-currency system) that COs expose. The Portable Reputation portfolio (Paper 4) stores CO scenarios as evidence of informed decision-making. Together, these layers create a socio-technical system in which the question "What might my participation look like?" receives an answer that is interactive, transparent, conservative, role-specific, mentor-guided, and durable.

The phrase "PLAY WITH THESE NUMBERS" is, in the end, an invitation not to fantasy but to literacy. By giving members the tools to construct and evaluate their own economic scenarios within the constraints of the cooperative model, COs transform the act of "playing" with numbers into the practice of understanding them.

---

